What is Circular Dependency?
A circular dependency occurs when two or more beans depend on each other directly or indirectly,
forming a loop.

Example:

Bean A depends on Bean B
Bean B depends on Bean A
This causes Spring to fail during bean creation, as it cannot resolve which bean to instantiate
first.

How to Avoid Circular Dependency

1. Refactor Your Design
Break the cycle:
Rethink your architecture so that beans don’t depend on each other directly.
Use interfaces or abstraction to decouple logic.
Move shared logic to a third bean that both depend on.

Example:

@Component
public class NotificationService { /* ... */ }

@Component
public class UserService {
    private final NotificationService notificationService;
    public UserService(NotificationService notificationService) { /* ... */ }
}

Here, both services are independent, or depend on a common bean, not each other.
2. Use Setter Injection (Only if Necessary)
Setter injection can help break the cycle, as Spring can create beans first and inject
dependencies later.
Note: This is a workaround, not a recommended solution for required dependencies.

Example:

@Component
public class A {
    private B b;
    @Autowired
    public void setB(B b) { this.b = b; }
}

@Component
public class B {
    private A a;
    @Autowired
    public void setA(A a) { this.a = a; }
}
This allows Spring to instantiate both beans before wiring them.
3. Use Events or Callbacks
Instead of direct dependencies, use Spring’s event mechanism or callbacks to communicate
between beans.

Example:

Bean A publishes an event.
Bean B listens for the event and reacts.
4. Re-examine Responsibilities
If two beans depend on each other, they may be doing too much.
Split responsibilities into smaller, focused beans.
5. Use @Lazy Annotation (Advanced)
You can use @Lazy to defer bean creation until it’s actually needed, which can help in rare
cases.

Example:

@Component
public class A {
    @Autowired
    @Lazy
    private B b;
}

This is a last resort and not recommended for most designs.